data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort → Cooperative Cancellation

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout enforcement**

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a thread that exceeds a deadline. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also removed (`SYSLIB0006`).

---

### What each removed API was doing

| Old API | Purpose in your code |
|---|---|
| `thread.Abort()` | Forcibly terminate the worker thread on timeout |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Catch the injected abort exception |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Swallow the abort so the thread could exit gracefully |

---

### Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the
            // token fires, even if the delegate itself doesn't check it.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ae.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If the work itself must respond to cancellation (recommended)

The above unblocks the *caller* after the timeout, but the delegate may keep running on the thread pool. For true cooperative cancellation, accept a `CancellationToken` in the work:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller usage:
// executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
// {
//     foreach (var item in items)
//     {
//         token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // cooperative checkpoint
//         Process(item);
//     }
//     return result;
// }, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

---

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Details |
|---|---|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If your `Func<T>` is a long CPU-bound call that never checks the token, it will keep running after the caller gets `TimeoutException`. You've abandoned it, not killed it. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` with a timer (`new CTS(timeout)`) leaks an internal `Timer` if not disposed. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` vs the actual task** | `Task.WaitAsync(token)` lets the *wait* abort, but the underlying `Task` keeps running. This is the closest equivalent to the old behavior where `Thread.Abort` didn't guarantee instant cleanup either. |
| **Blocking on async code** | `.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` keeps the method synchronous (matching your original API). If callers can go async, prefer `await task.WaitAsync(cts.Token)` to avoid deadlocks in UI/ASP.NET contexts. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If `work` calls into a library you can't modify to accept a token, there is no .NET 8 equivalent of `Thread.Abort`. Move that work to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()` as the last resort. |

---

### Validation Checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort` / `ThreadAbortException` / `Thread.ResetAbort`
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` is disposed via `using`
- ✅ Timeout throws `TimeoutException` (same behavior as original)
- ✅ Exceptions from work are propagated
- ✅ Builds cleanly on `net8.0` with no `SYSLIB0006` warnings
